HandsOnMORE

Maider Aguerralde Martin & Ángeles Arzalluz

2025-01-20

MORE (Multi-Omics REgulation) is an R package which is designed to infer condition-specific multi-omic regulatory networks. Developed by the BiostatOmics Lab, it is publicly available on the BiostatOmics GitHub repository.

MORE uses either Multiple Linear Regression (MLR) or Partial Least Squares (PLS) to model the expression of the features of a target omic as a function of experimental variables (e.g., disease or treatment) and the target feature’s potential regulators. For MLR, it applies advanced variable selection techniques such as ElasticNet or Iterative Sparse Group Lasso while for PLS, it uses Jack-Knife or Permutation techniques in combination with the Variable Importance in Projection (VIP) to identify the significant regulators of the target omic feature expression for the biological system under study. Additionally, MORE can incorporate prior regulatory knowledge and clinical data.

Installation

Currently, the package can be directly installed from GitHub using the devtools R package by:

install.packages("devtools")
devtools::install_github("BiostatOmics/MORE")

For a more comprenhensive overview of MORE functionalities, refer to the User Guide available here.

For further information on the methodological details, visit the preprint of the paper.

Data

In this tutorial, we will use the STATegra dataset, available HERE. A reduced version of this data is included in MORE as example data.

The STATegra dataset contains time-series data for pre-B-cell differentiation in mice, including 6 time points (0h, 2h, 6h, 12h, 18h, 24h). A set of samples has been subjected to drug-controlled induction of the Ikaros transcription factor, while the Control cells have not and, therefore, will not differentiate into B-cells.

First, load the data as follows:

load('DataSTATegra.RData')

DataSTATegra loads the following objects:

  • GeneExpressionDE: RNA-seq data. Matrix with differentially expressed genes across conditions in rows and samples in columns.

  • data.omics: List including each of the regulatory omics of the RNA-seq. Each omic is included in the list as a matrix with regulators in rows and samples in features.

  • associations: List containing pairs of gene-regulator known to interact, based on the literature and/or databases.

  • edesign: Matrix including the experimental design for each sample.

Important: MORE requires that the GeneExpression matrix and all matrices of the regulatory omics contain data from the same samples and in the same order. If sample labels differ, MORE will assume that samples are in the same order.

Below, we preview each object to demonstrate how to format input data for MORE.

Running MORE

To run MORE, for any of its possible model types, we use the function more(). The user can specify the type of regression model (one of MLR, PLS1 or PLS2) with the parameter method and the variable selection method to apply with the varSel parameter (EN or ISGL for MLR or Jack or Perm for PLS1 or PLS2).

However, some parameters are common for any regression or variable selection technique used:

  • omicType: A vector with as many elements as the number of omics, indicating whether each omic contains numeric (0) or binary (1) values. If not specified, MORE will automatically detect the omic types. However, the user MUST stop the process if the automatic detection is incorrect.

  • minVariation: A vector specifying the minimum required variation across conditions for a regulator to be included in the model.

  • scaleType: Indicates the type of scaling to be used (one of auto, softBlock or hardBlock).

  • interactions: By default, it is set to TRUE to allow MORE to test condition-dependent regulatory interactions. This effectively increases the number of predictors in the model but provides more interpretable information.

  • parallel: By default, FALSE. Considers parallelization in numberOfCores-1 when TRUE or the number of cores the user asks when a number is provided.

Note: MLR and PLS1 models create a model for each of the target omic features provided. PLS2 creates a unique model for all the target omic features but cannot consider prior regulatory knowledge.

In this tutorial, the data we would use has already been partially preprocessed. We will apply low filtering thresholds to those regulatory omics that were not/barely filtered and left it at 0 for those already filtered.

## omic order: "miRNA"  "DNase"  "Methyl" "TF"
minVar = c(0, 0.1, 0.1, 0)
names(minVar) = names(data.omics)

MORE requires a single covariate representing sample conditions. In this dataset, we have information about the time and the type of the treatment, but we will only create MORE models to compare Ikaros vs control samples.

edesign = edesign[,-1, drop=FALSE]

MLR + EN

This is how a MLR model with ElasticNet variable selection would be run:

MLRmodel = more(targetData = GeneExpressionDE,
                regulatoryData = data.omics,
                associations = associations,
                condition = edesign,
                omicType = 0,
                scaleType = 'auto',
                interactions = TRUE,
                minVariation = minVar,
                varSel = 'EN',
                alfaEN = NULL,
                correlation = 0.7,
                method = 'MLR',
                parallel = FALSE)

Results

MLRmodel output is a list containing the following objects:

names(MLRmodel)
## [1] "ResultsPerTargetF" "GlobalSummary"     "arguments"

ResultsPerTargetF

The list ResultsPerTargetF contains one object for each target feature (genes in this example). For example, we show the information MORE returns for the gene ENSMUSG00000000078:

  • Y: A data.frame with observed, fitted, and residual values for the target gene.

  • X: A data.frame containing the predictor variables included in the model.

  • coefficients: A matrix with the estimated coefficients for the selected regulators. The sign and magnitude of the coefficients indicate the direction and the strength of each association.

  • allRegulators: A data.frame with all the potential regulators in rows and the following information in the columns: gene, regulator, omic, area (the third optional column in the associations table), filter (whether the regulator has been filtered out of the model, and the reason) and Rel (1 if the model has selected the regulator or 0 if not).

  • relevantRegulators: A character vector containing the IDs of the relevant regulators selected by the model. If a “representative” of multicollinear regulators (mc) is detected as relevant, all the correlated regulators are also retrieved.

Note that some regulator include _mc1_ followed by a number and letters R, N and P appended to their IDs (e.g. mc1_1_P). These suffixes indicate relationships within highly correlated subgroups of regulators. More in detail, the first number indicates the subgroup of highly connected regulators in the correlation network, e.g. there may be two clusters of similarly correlated regulators, each of which has included a representative in the model: mc1_1 and mc1_2. The suffix _R means that this regulator was selected as the representative for its group, while _N and _P mean that the regulator is negatively or positively correlated with its representative, respectively.

GlobalSummary

The list GlobalSummary contains the general results of the models created. We show the information MORE returns:

  • TargetFNOregu: A matrix containing information about the genes with no initial regulators.

  • TargetFNOmodel: A matrix containing information about the genes for which MLR models could not be fitted and the reason why (either an error during MLR fit or a lack of regulators remaining after elastic net variable selection).

  • GoodnessOfFit: A matrix that collects the R-squared value, the Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE), the Normalized RMSE (NRMSE), and the number of relevant regulators selected by the model. This information could help filter results, for instance, by selecting the regulatory models that best explain the gene variance across the conditions.

  • ReguPerTargetF: A matrix containing, for each omic and gene, the number of initial regulators supplied (-Ini), the number of regulators included in the initial model (-Mod) after the series of filters applied by MORE, and the number of relevant regulators included in the final model (-Rel).

  • GlobalRegulators: A vector of the most relevant regulators, i.e., those relevant for a larger part of the genes. It selects the third quartile of the regulators after ranking them by their number of regulations.

  • HubTargetF: A vector of genes that accumulate more regulators, according to the MORE models. The third quartile of the gene list ranked by the number of regulators.

MLR + ISGL

To run MORE with Iterative Sparse Group Lasso variable selection, we would run:

MLRISGLmodel = more(targetData = GeneExpressionDE,
                regulatoryData = data.omics,
                associations = associations,
                condition = edesign,
                omicType = 0,
                scaleType = 'auto',
                interactions = TRUE,
                minVariation = minVar,
                varSel = 'ISGL',
                groupingISGL = 'MF_0.7',
                method = 'MLR')

As shown, we slightly changed the main function’s parameters. In this case, we used groupingISGL instead of alfaEN to change from the EN alfa mixing parameter to the type of approach to consider when creating the groups in the ISGL. In this example, we used the multicollinearity approach (MF) with a correlation threshold of 0.7 to make the groups. Other options:

  • MF_X: Takes the same approach as in the multicollinearity filter. Grouping the variables which correlate more than X.
  • PCA_X: Extracts as many PCA components to explain X percent of the variability of the data and assigns the variables to the component in which they had the highest loadings.

PLS1 + Jack + VIP

To run MORE with Partial Least Squares (PLS), we slightly change the parameters of the main function. In this case, we would use alfa instead of alfaEN to change from EN alfa mixing parameter to alpha (I type error) threshold to consider a p-value significant.

In the case of PLS models, we would talk about significant regulators instead of relevant regulators. So outputs like ResultsPerTargetF$relevantRegulators change to outputs like ResultsPerTargetF$significantRegulators.

To run a PLS model with Jack-Knife as variable selection technique, we can run:

PLSJackmodel = more(targetData = GeneExpressionDE,
                regulatoryData = data.omics,
                associations = associations,
                condition = edesign,
                omicType = 0,
                scaleType = 'auto',
                interactions = TRUE,
                minVariation = minVar,
                varSel = 'Jack',
                alfa = 0.05,
                method = 'PLS1')

PLS1 + Perm + VIP

To run a PLS model with Permutation as variable selection technique, we can run:

PLS1model = more(targetData = GeneExpressionDE,
                regulatoryData = data.omics,
                associations = associations,
                condition = edesign,
                omicType = 0,
                scaleType = 'auto',
                interactions = TRUE,
                minVariation = minVar,
                varSel = 'Perm',
                alfa = 0.05,
                method = 'PLS1')

PLS2

All the above-presented models compute a unique model for each gene considered. However, when there is no prior regulatory knowledge, it could be beneficial to run a PLS2, which creates a unique model for all the genes. To do so, we run:

PLS2mmodel = more(targetData = GeneExpressionDE,
                regulatoryData = data.omics,
                condition = edesign,
                omicType = 0,
                scaleType = 'auto',
                interactions = TRUE,
                minVariation = minVar,
                varSel = 'Perm',
                alfa = 0.05,
                method = 'PLS2')

Interpretating MORE results

We will be using the results from the PLS model with Jack-Knife variable selection to show the results of the various functionalities MORE incorporates.

First, we run the RegulationPerCondition() function, which returns a summary of the significant regulations for each gene. We will load the pre-computed results for all genes afterwards to avoid excessive runtime:

regpcond = RegulationPerCondition(PLSJackmodel)
load('RegulationperConditionPLS.RData')
head(regpcond)
##              targetF regulator omic     area Group_0 Group_1
## 1 ENSMUSG00000000028      Cux1   TF promoter  0.3306  0.3306
## 2 ENSMUSG00000000028      E2f2   TF promoter  0.5325  0.5325
## 3 ENSMUSG00000000028      Elk4   TF promoter -0.5081 -0.5081
## 4 ENSMUSG00000000028      Fli1   TF promoter -0.1625 -0.1625
## 5 ENSMUSG00000000028     Foxm1   TF promoter  0.7202  0.7202
## 6 ENSMUSG00000000028     Foxo1   TF   public -0.1749 -0.1749

Looking at the results of regpcond, we first make clear that Group_0 and Group_1 correspond to the Control and Ikaros conditions, respectively (as codified in edesign). The condition-specific coefficients can be interpreted as follows:

  • If two experimental groups have the same coefficients, the regulator has the same effect on the gene in both conditions.

  • If the coefficient is 0 in one of the groups, the regulator has no effect on the gene under that condition.

  • Experimental conditions with different, non-zero coefficients indicate that the regulator affects the gene in these conditions, but the magnitude of the effect is not the same for the groups.

regpcondMLR = RegulationPerCondition(MLRmodel)

To further explore the results of MORE, we can start with some summary plots of the computed models.

The summaryPlot function represents the percentage of genes with relevant regulations and the percentage of regulations found to be relevant in each omic, depending on whether the bytargetF parameter is set to TRUE or FALSE. We can also stratify the results filtering by \(R^2\), e.g. see the percentage of genes for which the model explains at least 90% of the variance:

summaryPlot(PLSJackmodel, regpcond, filterR2 = 0.9)

summaryPlot(PLSJackmodel, regpcond, byTargetF = FALSE, filterR2 = 0.9)

Notice that transcription factors account for the majority of regulatory relationships and that, when looking at the percentage of regulations, all omic layers have more relevant regulations in the Ikaros condition, indicative of the activation of the gene regulation machinery as a result of the action of this transcription factor.

After this prior study, if one is interested in focusing their efforts on analyzing the regulatory networks of a subset of genes that were better modelled by MORE, they can use filterR2 to do so.

To create smaller regulatory networks, we will apply the filter previously used in this example.

In MORE there are two ways to obtain the subset of genes that showed an R2 above the one the users wants to consider. The first is:

regpcond_filtered = RegulationPerCondition(MLRmodel, filterR2 = 0.9)

However, in the cases were MORE found a high amount of significant regulations this can be very time consuming. So we recommend to use this second option specially designed to apply the filter:

regpcond_filtered = FilterRegulationPerCondition(output = PLSJackmodel, outputRegpcond = regpcond, filterR2 = 0.9)

To explore the differential regulators across experimental conditions and omics, MORE incorporates differentialRegPlot() function. It can be applied either to the full set of genes or to those filtered by the R2. In our case, we will apply it to the filtered subset of genes, as we will focus our efforts on analyzing the results for these specific genes. This plot can be easily obtained by:

differentialRegPlot(output = PLSJackmodel, outputRegpcond = regpcond_filtered)

MORE also provides functions for visualization to explore gene-regulator relationships for the pairs identified as significant by MORE.

When no specific regulator is provided, a plot is generated for each gene, displaying all its significant regulators for the gene, together with the gene’s expression pattern.

To show also how this plots could help us verify the correlated patters of the regulators detected by MORE, we will create those plot for the MLR with the ElasticNet models output.

Since our example gene has many relevant regulators, we will show the regulatory patterns of the Foxo1 TF, which is representative of the mc1_1 group of correlated regulators. In this group, the Gtf2b TF and the mmu-miR-1187 miRNA are positively and negatively correlated regulators with Foxo1, respectively. Observe how this results in the expected activation/repression regulatory patterns:

par(mfrow = c(1,3))
plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = "ENSMUSG00000000078", regulator = "Foxo1", order = TRUE)

plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = "ENSMUSG00000000078", regulator = "Gtf2b", order = TRUE)

plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = "ENSMUSG00000000078", regulator = "mmu-miR-1187",  order = TRUE)

Additionally, if a regulator is specified but no gene is provided, MORE will generate plots for all gene–regulator pairs in which that regulator was identified as significant. Let’s do this for miRNA mmu-miR-146a-5p, a miRNA that regulates 4 genes according to the MORE results:

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = NULL, regulator = "mmu-miR-146a-5p", 
         order = TRUE)
## 4 target features are regulated by mmu-miR-146a-5p

## [1] "ENSMUSG00000026426" "ENSMUSG00000026915" "ENSMUSG00000032383"
## [4] "ENSMUSG00000036890"

If the relationship between gen and regulator is difficult to discern in those plots, we can simplify them and try to see them in a scatterplot. Re-using the previous example:

plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = "ENSMUSG00000000078", regulator = "Foxo1", simplify =  TRUE)

Returning to the results of the PLS model, we can easily visualize the regulatory networks inferred by MORE using the following code:

networkMORE(regpcond_filtered, cytoscape = FALSE)

Since these networks can be complex to analyze directly in R, MORE includes an extension to export them for interactive exploration in Cytoscape. To enable this, Cytoscape MUST be open and operative before executing:

networkMORE(regpcond_filtered, cytoscape = TRUE)

This code creates the following networks:

To look only at the different regulations, we can create differential regulatory networks by:

networkMORE(regpcond_filtered, group1 = '0', group2 = '1', cytoscape = TRUE)

Downstream analysis

MORE package also includes several other functionalities to do a complete downstream analysis.

To use them, we first need an annotation file. In this example, we will download the mouse annotation dataset from Gene Ontology. Take into account that we need to format in the correct way the annotation so that can be used by MORE.

gene_ids = keys(org.Mm.eg.db, keytype = "ENSEMBL")
annotation = AnnotationDbi::select(org.Mm.eg.db,
                         keys = gene_ids,
                         columns = c('GO','ENSEMBL'),
                         keytype = "ENSEMBL")
## 'select()' returned 1:many mapping between keys and columns
GOIDs = unique(annotation$GO)
cl = c('GOID','DEFINITION','TERM')
go_def = AnnotationDbi::select(GO.db, keys=GOIDs, columns=cl, keytype="GOID")
## 'select()' returned 1:1 mapping between keys and columns
colnames(go_def) = c('GO','GO.definition','GO.term')

annotation = merge(annotation, go_def, by = 'GO', all.x = TRUE)
annotation = annotation[,c(2,1,6,5,3,4)]
annotation = annotation[-which(is.na(annotation$GO)),,drop=FALSE]

Over Representation Analysis (ORA)

If the user has an annotation matrix, they can run an ORA either for the hub target features or the target features regulated by the global regulators, indicating TRUE or FALSE, respectively, on the byHubsparameter. It can be easily done with the following code but in this case we will not run it.

regincond_ikaros = RegulationInCondition(regpcond_filtered, cond = '1')

ORA_ikaros = oraMORE(MLRmodel,regincond_ikaros, byHubs = TRUE, annotation = annotation)

ORA_ikaros_globtarget = oraMORE(MLRmodel,regincond_ikaros, byHubs = FALSE, annotation = annotation)

Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA)

Users can also perform a Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA) to compare the results between two experimental conditions. In this case, the analysis can be run as follows:

regincond_control = RegulationInCondition(regpcond_filtered, cond = '0')
regincond_ikaros = RegulationInCondition(regpcond_filtered, cond = '1')
gsea_out = gseaMORE(regincond_control,regincond_ikaros,  annotation = annotation,p.adjust.method = 'none')
## using 'fgsea' for GSEA analysis, please cite Korotkevich et al (2019).
## preparing geneSet collections...
## GSEA analysis...
## leading edge analysis...
## done...
clusterProfiler::dotplot(gsea_out,  split=".sign") +  facet_grid(.~.sign, labeller = as_labeller(c(activated = "Ikaros", suppressed = "Control")))

Finally, users may be interested in exploring the regulatory networks associated with a specific pathway—particularly one identified as altered during the GSEA. MORE makes this analysis straightforward.

For example, in the example we were analizing we could be interested in the mitochondrion pathway, so we can run the following to analyze it:

networkMORE(regpcond_filtered, cytoscape = TRUE,annotation = annotation, pathway = 'mitochondrion')
networkMORE(regpcond_filtered, group1 = '0',group2 = '1', cytoscape = TRUE,annotation = annotation, pathway = 'mitochondrion')
